ter's commitments to efficiency and planning on the one hand, and to equal educational opportunity on the other, reflect the larger national movement in educational policy. When these commitments came into conflict, Michael suggests, Carter's attempts to reconcile them reveal both his own shifting priorities and the complex social and political obstacles facing educational policymakers then and now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducation and statezUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzGeorgia. 4aEducation : Education Policy and Leadership. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Educational Assessment and Evaluation. 4aPolitics and Law : Presidency, The. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aEDUCATION / Decision-Making & Problem Solving.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147790840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477908/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles